message.content: {"reasoning":"Ground truth focuses on an impossible helicopter state: rotor blades are motionless while the helicopter is flying. The generated report concerns rendering/lighting: helicopter model appears as a solid black silhouette at night. No mention of rotor motion, hovering physics, or character oscillation; instead focuses on visual lighting. Thus they describe different bugs.","match":false}

Therefore the two reports refer to different bugs.","match":false}

The core symptom (boat displacement due to player movement) is absent, and the reported symptom (clipping through floor) is not in the ground truth.\nTherefore they describe different bugs.","match":false}

No mention of animal behavior or being propelled; no physics launch described. Conversely, ground truth says nothing about bow model mis-rendering. Therefore they reference different underlying issues.","match":false}

{"reasoning":"Ground truth focuses on a specific rendering error: an NPC is visible but missing its head, then the (still headless) NPC disappears. The essential symptoms are (1) the character is headless and (2) the character vanishes. \n\nThe generated report does mention a character that “appears to pop in and out of existence directly in front of the vehicle,” satisfying the disappearance aspect, but it never indicates that the character is missing its head. Instead, it describes the entire model popping in/out and adds unrelated problems (blurred view, lingering explosion effects). Because the defining ‘headless’ aspect is absent and the described visual issues differ, the two reports are not clearly about the same underlying bug.","match":false}

{"reasoning":"The ground truth bug concerns a visual/physics issue where a yellow/orange tanker truck is shaking and oscillating while everything else remains still. The generated bug report, however, discusses a UI text element (a player username) that is rendered incorrectly in the 3-D world and mentions unrelated NPC physics anomalies. There is no mention of a tanker truck, shaking/oscillation, or similar physics behavior. Likewise, the ground-truth bug has nothing to do with misplaced UI text. Hence, they describe entirely different problems.","match":false}

{"reasoning":"Both texts mention some form of clipping, but the specific behaviour they describe is different.  
• Ground truth: when the character pushes into a building the camera passes through the wall and the player can see the void behind it. The character’s world position is not altered – the problem is purely visual (camera-through-wall / inside-geometry).  
• Generated report: the moment the player approaches a blue door the character’s entire position is repeatedly teleported to totally different places (walkways, scaffolding, other town areas). This is a severe positional warp, not just a camera poking through a wall.  
The teleportation and multi-location jumps are the core of the generated report and are not present in the ground-truth description; conversely, the "void behind the wall" symptom that defines the ground-truth bug is never mentioned in the generated report. Therefore they are describing two different underlying bugs.","match":false}

{"reasoning":"Ground truth: when the player gets into a vehicle that already has an NPC in the driver seat, the camera clips into the NPC’s head so the player only sees a floating mouth / neck / back-of-head in front of the windshield.\nGenerated report: inside the vehicle view a persistent floating object that looks like a black shape with a red/pink interior \"resembling lips or a mouth\" blocks the view; it stays fixed relative to the camera in first-person vehicle view.\nBoth reports describe the same visual artefact: the camera ends up inside another character’s head, so the player sees the interior of that head (mouth/lips, back of head) obstructing the screen. The generated report omits the specific trigger (entering when NPC is already seated) but the symptom and context (first-person vehicle view, disembodied mouth showing) match. Therefore they refer to the same underlying bug.","match":true}
